               <msContents>
                  <summary>Encyclopedic anthology on topics such as the religious sciences, ethics, philosophy, polite learning and the interpretation of dreams, compiled from various texts, with supplement.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_457-item1">
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Muḥammad Saʻīd</persName>
                        
                        
                        
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">محمد سعيد‏
                           
                           
                           
                        </persName>
                        
                        
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc">Jung-i Kalām-i Ismāʿīlī</title>
                     
                     <title xml:lang="fa">جنگ کلام اسماعیلی</title>
                     
                     
                     <note>This work is an encyclopedic anthology on topics such as the religious sciences, ethics, philosophy, polite learning and the interpretation of dreams, compiled from various texts including Makārim al-akhlāq, Iḥyā ʿulūm al-dīn, Kashf al-niʿma, Rabīʿal-abrār, and Rasā’il ikhwān al-safā’.</note>
                     <note>Begins on<locus>f.78a</locus>(i.e. 1a).</note>
                     <note>Chapter markings disappear after Chapter Four.</note>
                     <note>The text was compiled for Abū l-Manṣūr Abū l-Naṣr al-Muẓaffar Sultān ‘Abdallāh Quṭb Shāh. On f. 76a it is recorded that the year in which the compiler was ordered to compose the work corresponded with the word intikhāb – i.e. 1054/1644-5.</note>
                     <note>The following represents a preliminary list of the work's chapters and their place in the manuscript [JW July 2017]:<list>
                           <item>
                              <locus>79a</locus>Introduction: on the definition of knowledge.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>80b</locus>On prayer, repeating the name of God, and using the bathhouse and toothpicks [sic].</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>89a</locus>On which work should be undertaken on which days of the week.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>90a</locus>On the months of the year.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>90b</locus>On the effects exerted on the human body by the seasons.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>92b</locus>On clothing.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>93a</locus>Chapter Two: on friendship and enmity.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>104a</locus>Chapter Three: on socializing with people and social conduct.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>125a</locus>Chapter Four: on clemency, punishment, repentance, and the acceptance of apology.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>136a</locus>Chapter on patience? Heading blank.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>145a</locus>Chapter on justice? Heading blank</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>167b</locus>Section – anecdotes on fools who were Arabs. Chapter unmarked.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>171a</locus>On intelligent fools.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>172b</locus>On praiseworthy things accomplished by intelligent men.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>175b</locus>On praise and blame.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>219a</locus>Chapter (marked) on the foundation of Islam and belief.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>229a</locus>On animal and plant life.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>230a</locus>On impure things (masūkhāt).</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>237a</locus>On the stratagems (ḥiyalhā) exhibited by some famous figures.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>245a</locus>On dreams and their interpretation.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>252b</locus>Main text ends.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>1a</locus>‘Supplement’, described as a separate epistle in reality, devoted to five words connected to kingship. Consists of five chapters and a conclusion.<list>
                                 <item>
                                    <locus>1a</locus>Introduction: on the meaning of the word ‘king’.</item>
                                 <item>
                                    <locus>12b</locus>Chapter Two: on the king’s counsel and judgement.</item>
                                 <item>
                                    <locus>27a</locus>Chapter Three: on seriousness (jidd) and the exertion of effort (jahd).</item>
                                 <item>
                                    <locus>38a</locus>Chapter Four: on the ordering of retainers and servants.</item>
                                 <item>
                                    <locus>50a</locus>On the customs and behavior of kings</item>
                              </list>
                           </item>
                        </list>
                     </note>
                     <note>The first page of volume 2 is missing.</note>
